You are a senior IT architect and technical storyteller.

I need you to create a professional presentation for an internal innovation program called
“The Good Engineer – Tech Innovation”.

The presentation must be structured slide-by-slide (SLIDE 1, SLIDE 2, etc.) and should be
designed for a 15-minute presentation.

IMPORTANT:
- Do NOT generate a PowerPoint file.
- Write the content slide by slide, with clear titles and bullet points.
- The audience is mixed: senior engineers + IT management.
- The solution is already implemented in production (this is NOT a proposal or POC).

You must strictly follow the criteria of the “Tech Innovation” category:
- Clear problem statement
- Implemented solution
- High-level architecture
- Technical implementation
- Measurable impact (cost, time, risk)
- Scalability and reusability
- Innovation through engineering decisions

--------------------------------------------------
CONTEXT / USE CASE
--------------------------------------------------

The subject of the presentation is the re-design of the IBM Db2 database architecture used by
IBM ECM (Enterprise Content Management).

INITIAL STATE (OLD SOLUTION):
- Architecture based on IBM Db2 pureScale
- 2 sites: PROD and DR
- Each site had 4 servers:
  - 2 Db2 Member servers
  - 2 Cluster Facility (CF) servers
- Shared-disk architecture
- Very complex operational model
- Disaster Recovery required:
  - Full shutdown of PROD
  - Manual storage synchronization performed by AIX/Storage teams
  - Manual startup in DR
- RTO was measured in hours
- Very high licensing cost for Db2 pureScale (~350,000 EUR per year)

PROBLEMS IDENTIFIED:
- Extremely high licensing cost
- Overly complex architecture
- High operational risk during DR
- Strong dependency on multiple teams (DBA, AIX, Storage)
- Slow and unpredictable DR procedures

--------------------------------------------------
NEW SOLUTION (IMPLEMENTED)
--------------------------------------------------

The architecture was redesigned and migrated to IBM Db2 HADR.

NEW ARCHITECTURE:
- Total of 4 servers
- 2 servers in PROD site
- 2 servers in DR site
- HADR topology:
  - 1 Primary
  - 3 Standby servers
- Shared-nothing architecture
- Synchronous and asynchronous HADR replication
- DR failover performed using a single command:
  - `db2 takeover hadr`
- RTO reduced from hours to seconds

--------------------------------------------------
PERFORMANCE & STORAGE DESIGN
--------------------------------------------------

As part of the redesign, a performance-oriented filesystem layout was implemented.
Each filesystem is placed on its own dedicated physical disk.

Filesystem layout:
- 1 filesystem dedicated to CUSTOS database data (largest database)
- 1 filesystem dedicated to BSUPOD database data (second largest)
- 1 filesystem for all remaining (small) databases
- 1 filesystem for CUSTOS transaction logs
- 1 filesystem for BSUPOD transaction logs
- 1 filesystem for transaction logs of the remaining databases
- 1 filesystem for archived transaction logs
- 1 filesystem dedicated to database backups

This design improved:
- I/O isolation
- Log write performance
- Recovery speed
- Predictability under load

--------------------------------------------------
WHAT TO INCLUDE IN THE PRESENTATION
--------------------------------------------------

Please generate:
- Clear slide titles
- Well-structured bullet points
- Strong technical explanation, but understandable by management
- Explicit comparison between OLD vs NEW architecture
- Financial impact (cost savings)
- Operational impact (simplicity, risk reduction)
- Scalability and reuse potential
- A clear explanation of why this is a Tech Innovation
- Professional, enterprise-level tone (not marketing, not academic)

--------------------------------------------------
EXPECTED OUTPUT FORMAT
--------------------------------------------------

SLIDE 1 – Title
SLIDE 2 – Business & Technical Context
SLIDE 3 – Problem Statement
SLIDE 4 – Old Architecture (Db2 pureScale)
SLIDE 5 – Limitations of Old Architecture
SLIDE 6 – Redesign Objectives
